result.execSummary:
The deferred prosecution or sentencing agreement(s) on this case were fulfilled, and the charge(s) were dismissed.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant Cali G Dunn in court.  Attorney Glenn Edward Gaskill III in court for Cali G Dunn.  Prosecuting attorney Brad Alan Vorpahl in court for the State of Wisconsin. 
The defendant has complied with the Deferred Prosecution Agreement.  On motion of the State, Court ordered case dismissed with prejudice.

Defendant Cali G Dunn in court with attorney Adam Kachelski on behalf of Glenn Edward Gaskill.  Brad Alan Vorpahl appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Cali G Dunn appeared by video means with Attorney.  Deputy Court Clerk: AMI
Case heard via Zoom. 
Defendant completed all requirements.   Based upon the defendant's compliance with the Deferred Prosecution Agreement, matter is adjourned for Final Review Hearing.
  This case will be heard via Zoom. Zoom meeting information provided to parties.
  Pursuant to Chief Judge Directive 22-04, parties are hereby notified that effective July 30, 2022 this case will be assigned to branch 17, Judge Carolina Stark, in Room 310 of the Safety Building.  Review hearing scheduled for August 30, 2022 at 10:20 am.
